59    /**
60    * Base class for all nodes of the abstract syntax tree.
61    * <h2>Construction</h2>
62    * <p>The tree is built by instantiating the required nodes, then adding them to other nodes.
63    * If it is the parser who is building the tree, it will use the largest constructor,
64    * the one with "range" as the first parameter.
65    * If you want to manually instantiate nodes, we suggest to...
66    * <ul>
67    * <li>use a convenience method, like "addStatement(...)", or if none are available...</li>
68    * <li>use a convenient constructor, like ClassOrInterfaceType(String name), or if none are available...</li>
69    * <li>use the default constructor.</li>
70    * <li>Alternatively, use one of the JavaParser.parse(snippet) methods.</li>
71    * </ul>
72    * ... and use the various methods on the node to initialize it further, if needed.
73    * <h2>Parent/child</h2>
74    * <p>The parent node field is managed automatically and can be seen as read only.
75    * Note that there is only one parent,
76    * and trying to use the same node in two places will lead to unexpected behaviour.
77    * It is advised to clone() a node before moving it around.
78    * <h2>Comments</h2>
79    * <p>Each Node can have one associated comment which describes it and
80    * a number of "orphan comments" which it contains but are not specifically
81    * associated to any child.
82    * <h2>Positions</h2>
83    * <p>When the parser creates nodes, it sets their source code position in the "range" field.
84    * When you manually instantiate nodes, their range is not set.
85    * The top left character is position 1, 1.
86    * Note that since this is an <i>abstract</i> syntax tree,
87    * it leaves out a lot of text from the original source file,
88    * like where braces or comma's are exactly.
89    * Therefore there is no position information on everything in the original source file.
90    * <h2>Observers</h2>
91    * <p>It is possible to add observers to the the tree.
92    * Any change in the tree is sent as an event to any observers watching.
93    * <h2>Visitors</h2>
94    * <p>The most comfortable way of working with an abstract syntax tree is using visitors.
95    * You can use one of the visitors in the visitor package, or extend one of them.
96    * A visitor can be "run" by calling accept on a node:
97    * <pre>node.accept(visitor, argument);</pre>
98    * where argument is an object of your choice (often simply null.)
99    *
100    * @author Julio Vilmar Gesser
101    */
